    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n8080" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πρό-φρων</span></b> , <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ονος</span> (<span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">φρήν</span>):
          adj., regularly used not as attributive but as adverb,
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">cheerful</span>(<span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">ly</span>),
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">gracious</span>(<span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">ly</span>), <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">kind-</span>
            (<span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">ly</span>), <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">zealous</span>(<span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">ly</span>),
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">earnest</span>(<span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">ly</span>)<span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">;</span> ironical,
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πρόφρων κεν δὴ ἔπειτα Δία λιτοίμην</span>,
          ‘in good earnest,’ i. e. I could not do it, <i><span class="en">Od. 14.406</span></i>; as adj., <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">θῡμῷ
            πρόφρονι</span>, <i><span class="en">Il. 8.40</span></i>.—Adv.,
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">προφρονέως</span> (Il.).</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
    <div class="alpheios-lex-alph-source">From <u>
            <u>A Homeric Dictionary</u>
        </u> (Georg Autenrieth, New York, Harper and Brothers, 1891) </div>
